    {
      "question": "If $\\alpha$ and $\\beta$ are the roots of the quadratic equation $x^2 - 7x + 12 = 0$, then the quadratic equation whose roots are $\\alpha + 2$ and $\\beta + 2$ is:",
      "answer": "(C)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Find the roots of the given equation $x^2 - 7x + 12 = 0$ by factorisation.",
          "Factorise $x^2 - 4x - 3x + 12 = 0$ to get $(x-4)(x-3) = 0$, so $\\alpha=4$ and $\\beta=3$.",
          "Determine the new roots: $\\alpha + 2 = 6$ and $\\beta + 2 = 5$.",
          "Form the new quadratic equation using $(x-6)(x-5) = 0$.",
          "Expand to get $x^2 - 11x + 30 = 0$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$x^2 - 7x + 12 = 0 \\\\ x^2 - 4x - 3x + 12 = 0 \\\\ x(x-4) - 3(x-4) = 0 \\\\ (x-4)(x-3) = 0 \\\\ \\alpha = 4, \\beta = 3 \\\\ \\text{New roots: } 4+2=6, 3+2=5 \\\\ (x-6)(x-5) = 0 \\\\ x^2 - 5x - 6x + 30 = 0 \\\\ x^2 - 11x + 30 = 0$"
      },
      "topic": "Quadratic Equations",
      "subtopic": "factorisation method",
      "marks": 1,
